 of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cailly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghailligh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghailleach</i>’. Compare   Crawley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crawley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Crawley, for example in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Sussex, and Oxfordshire, named with Old English <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Crowley  .","Irish (Louth): in Ireland, this is generally the English name in 1 above, but it may also have been adopted for <b>McCrawley</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghallaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghallach</i>’, also Anglicized as <b>Magreely</b>."]},{"name":"Crilley","meanings":["Irish (Derry): variant of   Crilly  ."]},{"name":"Kriley","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Irish   Crilly  ."]},{"name":"Grilley","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of Irish   Crilly  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John De Cailly Lord of Massingham was born about 1150, in Great Massingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Cailly Lord of Massingham, was 17 and his mother, Beatrice, was 17. He married Beatrice de Butery in 1165. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died after 1202, in his hom